-- South African Equities Surge Most in Five Months as Metals Prices Advance
-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 2011-02-02T17:30:33Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-02/south-africa-stocks-have-biggest-two-day-gain-in-three-weeks.html
South African stocks climbed the most
in five months, led by  Anglo American Plc  and  BHP Billiton Plc ,
after copper fluctuated near record highs and base metals rose.  The FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index gained 2 percent, the
most since Sept. 1, to 32,487.61 by the 5 p.m. close in
Johannesburg, taking its two-day gain to 3.5 percent, the
biggest since June 10. Anglo, which makes up 11 percent of the
benchmark index, led advances, rallying 4.5 percent to 371.35
rand, the highest since September 2008. BHP had a third day of
gains, rising to 289 rand, the highest since July 2008.  Copper reached records after figures yesterday showed
manufacturing expanded in the U.S., Europe, China and India.
Copper for March delivery gained 0.2 cent to $4.549 a pound
at 11:41 a.m. on the Comex in  New York  after touching $4.562.
Prices added as much as 0.3 percent and slid as much as 0.7
percent. Tin, zinc and lead advanced on the London Metal
Exchange.  To contact the reporter on this story:
